    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During a high-intensity interval training (HIIT) session, your muscles produce lactic acid due to anaerobic respiration when oxygen is insufficient for full energy production. This lactic acid provides quick energy and masks the pain or fatigue you'd feel. Once you stop exercising, your body uses lactate conversion to glucose in the liver, a process known as the Cori cycle, and muscle cells also begin to clear the lactic acid, often leading to a temporary burn during and after your workout.",
