    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it's still kinda weird. it's like there's all these tiny things just piling up in there causing the burn. is it basically just a build up of waste products that's messing with the muscle cells? how's it actually causing the physical sensation of pain?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid build-up in your muscles during intense exercise does contribute to the sensation of burning. As lactic acid forms, it dissociates into lactate and hydrogen ions. The hydrogen ions increase acidity within the muscle cells, which can interfere with enzyme function and lead to cell stress. This cellular stress can stimulate pain receptors, giving you that burning sensation. The body gets rid of accumulated lactic acid by converting lactate back to glucose in the liver and then clearing it from the muscles, usually increasing its clearance rate after exercise, which can cause the muscle burn you feel during recovery.",
      "source": "target",
